`crates/ctx-cage/src` is the whole `ctx-cage` crate: it sandboxes an agent run in a bwrap namespace with no direct network, brokers or proxies its only egress, and offers exactly one host-side flow — `cli::resolve_mode` → `lifecycle::execute` — plus a separate in-cage client binary that speaks back over a UNIX socket. Depending on this crate as a whole gets you the three `bin/` executables; depending on a submodule gets you a narrow piece (argv construction, wire protocol, proxying, runtime resolution) documented in its own rollup/ctx.

The cage's guarantees are stated once, in `lib.rs`'s doc comment, and are binding on `bwrap/` and `runtime.rs`: workspace mounted read-write at its real host path (no alias, ADR-046), toolchain read-only, `.env`/`.git/config` masked, `$HOME` untouched except the one bound credentials file, fresh namespaces, `no_new_privs`, network fully offline except the proxy socket. `CAGE_RULES_MD` (compiled in from `../assets/cage-rules.md`) must be injected via `--append-system-prompt-file` on every real claude launch — any new launcher path has to preserve this or safety doctrine silently stops applying.

Two parallel host↔cage boundaries exist and must not be conflated: `proxy.rs` (raw HTTP/TLS relay, used by `lifecycle::run`, forwards claude's own OAuth token, real API key injected host-side only when `ProxyConfig.api_key` is `Some`) and `broker.rs`+`protocol.rs`+`spawn.rs` (allowlisted tool-call brokering, used by `lifecycle::serve`, consumed by `bin/ctx_cage_client.rs` on the wire format in `protocol.rs`). `error.rs`'s `CageError` is the shared return type across all of these — Io/Json only via `#[from]`, everything else collapses to `Protocol`. `runtime.rs` supplies the billed-mode credential/config synthesis that `lifecycle::prepare` calls before either run path launches. `summarize.rs` is unrelated to sandboxing proper — it's the `.ctx` leaf-staleness detector `bin/ctx_run.rs` calls post-run to refresh summaries.

Cross-cutting invariant: `target_root` is canonicalized once in `lifecycle::mod.rs` before any `bwrap` config assembly, because both bwrap builders and `runtime.rs`'s trust-map key assume the absolute host path; nothing else re-canonicalizes it.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.